[src:materialize-db/incremental-computing] An automated incremental computing tool is a specialised program analysis tool for optimization.
[src:materialize-db/incremental-computing] Some approaches to incremental computing are specialized, while others are general purpose.
[src:materialize-db/incremental-computing] Specialized approaches require the programmer to explicitly specify the algorithms and data structures that will be used to preserve unchanged sub-calculations.
[src:materialize-db/incremental-computing] General-purpose approaches, on the other hand, use language, compiler, or algorithmic techniques to give incremental behavior to otherwise non-incremental programs.
[src:materialize-db/incremental-computing] Given a computation $C=f(x_{1},x_{2},\dots x_{n})$ and a potential change $x_{j}:=\Delta _{x_{j}}$ , we can insert code before the change occurs (the pre-derivative) and after the change (the post-derivative) to update the value of C faster than rerunning f .
[src:materialize-db/incremental-computing] Paige has written down a list of rules for formal differentiation of programs in SUBSETL.
[src:materialize-db/incremental-computing] In database systems such as DBToaster, views are defined with relational algebra.
[src:materialize-db/incremental-computing] *Incremental view maintenance* statically analyzes relational algebra to create update rules that quickly maintain the view in the presence of small updates, such as insertion of a row.
[src:materialize-db/incremental-computing] Incremental computation can be achieved by building a dependency graph of all the data elements that may need to be recalculated, and their dependencies.
[src:materialize-db/incremental-computing] The elements that need to be updated when a single element changes are given by the transitive closure of the dependency relation of the graph.
[src:materialize-db/incremental-computing] In other words, if there is a path from the changed element to another element, the latter may be updated (depending on whether the change eventually reaches the element).
[src:materialize-db/incremental-computing] The dependency graph may need to be updated as dependencies change, or as elements are added to, or removed from, the system.
[src:materialize-db/incremental-computing] It is used internally by the implementation, and does not typically need to be displayed to the user.
[src:materialize-db/incremental-computing] Partial evaluation can be combined with other incremental computing techniques.
[src:materialize-db/incremental-computing] With cycles in the dependency graph, a single pass through the graph may not be sufficient to reach a fixed point.
[src:materialize-db/incremental-computing] In some cases, complete re-evaluation of a system is semantically equivalent to incremental evaluation, and may be more efficient in practice if not in theory.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Materialize is a real-time data integration platform that creates and continually updates consistent views of transactional data from across your organization.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Its SQL interface democratizes the ability to serve and access live data.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Materialize can be deployed anywhere your infrastructure runs.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Use Materialize to do things like deliver fresh context for AI/RAG pipelines, power operational dashboards, and create more dynamic customer experiences without building time-consuming custom data pipelines.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] You can sign up for a free cloud trial or download our community edition, which is free forever for deployments using less than 24 GiB of memory and 48 GiB of disk!
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Materialize focuses on providing correct and consistent answers with minimal latency, and does not ask you to accept either approximate answers or eventual consistency.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] This guarantee holds even when joining data from multiple upstream systems.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Whenever Materialize answers a query, that answer is the correct result on some specific (and recent) version of your data.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Materialize does all of this by recasting your SQL queries as *dataflows*, which can react efficiently to changes in your data as they happen.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Our fully managed service is cloud-native, featuring **high availability** through multi-active replication, **horizontal scalability** by seamlessly scaling dataflows across multiple machines, and **near-infinite storage** by leveraging cloud object storage (e.g., Amazon S3).
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] You can self-manage Materialize using our Enterprise or Community editions.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] We support a large fraction of PostgreSQL features and are actively expanding support for more built-in PostgreSQL functions.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Please file an issue if you have an idea for an improvement!
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Materialize can read data directly from a PostgreSQL or MySQL replication stream, from Kafka (and other Kafka API-compatible systems like Redpanda), or from SaaS applications via webhooks.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Once you've got the data in, define views and perform reads via the PostgreSQL protocol.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Use your favorite SQL client, including the `psql` you probably already have on your system.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Customers using Materialize in production tend to use dbt Core.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] We’ve also extended our SQL support to enable recursion that supports incrementally updating tree and graph structures.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Stream inserts, updates, and deletes on the underlying tables (`lineitem` and `supplier`), and Materialize keeps the materialized view incrementally updated.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] You can type `SELECT * FROM tpch_q15` and expect to see the current results immediately!
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Materialize is provided as a self-managed product and a fully managed cloud service with credit-based pricing.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Included in the price are proprietary cloud-native features like horizontal scalability, high availability, and a web management console.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] We're big believers in advancing the frontier of human knowledge.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] To that end, the source code of the standalone database engine is publicly available, in this repository, and licensed under the BSL 1.1, converting to the open-source Apache 2.0 license after 4 years.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] As stated in the BSL, use of the standalone database engine on a single node is free forever.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Materialize depends upon many open source Rust crates.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] We maintain a list of these crates and their licenses, including links to their source repositories.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Materialize is primarily written in Rust.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Developers can find docs at doc/developer, and Rust API documentation is hosted at https://dev.materialize.com/api/rust/.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Prospective code contributors might find the D-good for external contributors discussion label useful.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] See CONTRIBUTING.md for additional guidance.
[src:materialize-db/main-readme-md] Materialize is lovingly crafted by a team of developers and one bot.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] In computing, a **materialized view** is a database object that contains the results of a query.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] For example, it may be a local copy of data located remotely, or may be a subset of the rows and/or columns of a table or join result, or may be a summary using an aggregate function.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] The process of setting up a materialized view is sometimes called **materialization**.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] This is a form of caching the results of a query, similar to memoization of the value of a function in functional languages, and it is sometimes described as a form of precomputation.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] As with other forms of precomputation, database users typically use materialized views for performance reasons, i.e. as a form of optimization.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] Materialized views that store data based on remote tables were also known as snapshots (deprecated Oracle terminology).
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] In any database management system following the relational model, a view is a virtual table representing the result of a database query.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] Whenever a query or an update addresses an ordinary view's virtual table, the DBMS converts these into queries or updates against the underlying base tables.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] A materialized view takes a different approach: the query result is cached as a concrete ("materialized") table (rather than a view as such) that may be updated from the original base tables from time to time.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] This enables much more efficient access, at the cost of extra storage and of some data being potentially out-of-date.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] Materialized views find use especially in data warehousing scenarios, where frequent queries of the actual base tables can be expensive.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] In a materialized view, indexes can be built on any column.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] In contrast, in a normal view, it's typically only possible to exploit indexes on columns that come directly from (or have a mapping to) indexed columns in the base tables; often this functionality is not offered at all.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] Materialized views were implemented first by the Oracle Database: the Query rewrite feature was added from version 8i.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] In PostgreSQL, version 9.3 and newer natively support materialized views.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] In version 9.3, a materialized view is not auto-refreshed, and is populated only at time of creation (unless `WITH NO DATA` is used).
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] It may be refreshed later manually using `REFRESH MATERIALIZED VIEW`.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] In version 9.4, the refresh may be concurrent with selects on the materialized view if `CONCURRENTLY` is used.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] Microsoft SQL Server differs from other RDBMS by the way of implementing materialized view via a concept known as "Indexed Views".
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] The main difference is that such views do not require a refresh because they are in fact always synchronized to the original data of the tables that compound the view.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] To achieve this, it is necessary that the lines of origin and destination are "deterministic" in their mapping, which limits the types of possible queries to do this.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] This mechanism has been realised since the 2000 version of SQL Server.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] Apache Kafka (since v0.10.2), Apache Spark (since v2.0), Apache Flink, Kinetica DB, Materialize, RisingWave, and Epsio all support materialized views on streams of data.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] Materialized views are also supported in Sybase SQL Anywhere.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] In IBM Db2, they are called "materialized query tables".
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] ClickHouse supports materialized views that automatically refresh on merges.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] MySQL doesn't support materialized views natively, but workarounds can be implemented by using triggers or stored procedures or by using the open-source application Flexviews.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] Materialized views can be implemented in Amazon DynamoDB using data modification events captured by DynamoDB Streams.
[src:materialize-db/materialized-view] Google announced in 8 April 2020 the availability of materialized views for BigQuery as a beta release.
[src:materialize-db/page] Materialize is the live data layer for apps and AI agents.
[src:materialize-db/page] To keep results up-to-date as new data arrives, Materialize incrementally updates results as it ingests data rather than recalculating results from scratch.
[src:materialize-db/page] For more information on these and other changes, see the Release Notes.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Introduced in the 1970s, SQL offered two main advantages over older read–write APIs such as ISAM or VSAM.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Firstly, it introduced the concept of accessing many records with one single command.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Secondly, it eliminates the need to specify *how* to reach a record, i.e., with or without an index.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Originally based upon relational algebra and tuple relational calculus, SQL consists of many types of statements, which may be informally classed as sublanguages, commonly: data query language (DQL), data definition language (DDL), data control language (DCL), and data manipulation language (DML).
[src:materialize-db/sql] The scope of SQL includes data query, data manipulation (insert, update, and delete), data definition (schema creation and modification), and data access control.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Although SQL is essentially a declarative language (4GL), it also includes procedural elements.
[src:materialize-db/sql] SQL was one of the first commercial languages to use Edgar F.
[src:materialize-db/sql] The model was described in his influential 1970 paper, "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:materialize-db/sql] Despite not entirely adhering to the relational model as described by Codd, SQL became the most widely used database language.
[src:materialize-db/sql] SQL became a standard of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) in 1986 and of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1987.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Since then, the standard has been revised multiple times to include a larger set of features and incorporate common extensions.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Despite the existence of standards, virtually no implementations in existence adhere to it fully, and most SQL code requires at least some changes before being ported to different database systems.
[src:materialize-db/sql] SQL was initially developed at IBM by Donald D.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Boyce after learning about the relational model from Edgar F.
[src:materialize-db/sql] This version, initially called SEQUEL (Structured English Query Language), was designed to manipulate and retrieve data stored in IBM's original quasirelational database management system, System R, which a group at IBM San Jose Research Laboratory had developed during the 1970s.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Chamberlin and Boyce's first attempt at a relational database language was SQUARE (Specifying Queries in A Relational Environment), but it was difficult to use due to subscript/superscript notation.
[src:materialize-db/sql] After moving to the San Jose Research Laboratory in 1973, they began work on a sequel to SQUARE.
[src:materialize-db/sql] The original name SEQUEL, which is widely regarded as a pun on QUEL, the query language of Ingres, was later changed to SQL (dropping the vowels) because "SEQUEL" was a trademark of the UK-based Hawker Siddeley Dynamics Engineering Limited company.
[src:materialize-db/sql] The label SQL later became the acronym for Structured Query Language.
[src:materialize-db/sql] After testing SQL at customer test sites to determine the usefulness and practicality of the system, IBM began developing commercial products based on their System R prototype, including System/38, SQL/DS, and IBM Db2, which were commercially available in 1979, 1981, and 1983, respectively.
[src:materialize-db/sql] IBM's endorsement caused the industry to move to SQL from alternatives like QUEL.
[src:materialize-db/sql] In the late 1970s, Relational Software, Inc.
[src:materialize-db/sql] (now Oracle Corporation) saw the potential of the concepts described by Codd, Chamberlin, and Boyce, and developed their own SQL-based RDBMS with aspirations of selling it to the U.S.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Navy, Central Intelligence Agency, and other U.S. government agencies.
[src:materialize-db/sql] In June 1979, Relational Software introduced one of the first commercially available implementations of SQL, Oracle V2 (Version2) for VAX computers.
[src:materialize-db/sql] By 1986, ANSI and ISO standard groups officially adopted the standard "Database Language SQL" language definition.
[src:materialize-db/sql] SQL implementations are incompatible between vendors and do not necessarily completely follow standards.
[src:materialize-db/sql] In particular, date and time syntax, string concatenation, `NULL`s, and comparison case sensitivity vary from vendor to vendor.
[src:materialize-db/sql] PostgreSQL and Mimer SQL strive for standards compliance, though PostgreSQL does not adhere to the standard in all cases.
[src:materialize-db/sql] For example, the folding of unquoted names to lower case in PostgreSQL is incompatible with the SQL standard, which says that unquoted names should be folded to upper case.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Thus, according to the standard, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO`, not `foo`.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Popular implementations of SQL commonly omit support for basic features of Standard SQL, such as the `DATE` or `TIME` data types.
[src:materialize-db/sql] The most obvious such examples, and incidentally the most popular commercial and proprietary SQL DBMSs, are Oracle (whose `DATE` behaves as `DATETIME`, and lacks a `TIME` type) and MS SQL Server (before the 2008 version).
[src:materialize-db/sql] As a result, SQL code can rarely be ported between database systems without modifications.
[src:materialize-db/sql] SQL was adopted as a standard by the ANSI in 1986 as SQL-86 and the ISO in 1987.
[src:materialize-db/sql] It is maintained by *ISO/IEC JTC 1, Information technology, Subcommittee SC 32, Data management and interchange*.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Until 1996, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) data-management standards program certified SQL DBMS compliance with the SQL standard.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Vendors now self-certify the compliance of their products.
[src:materialize-db/sql] The original standard declared that the official pronunciation for "SQL" was an initialism: /ˌɛsˌkjuːˈɛl/ ("ess cue el").
[src:materialize-db/sql] Regardless, many English-speaking database professionals (including Donald Chamberlin himself) use the acronym-like pronunciation of /ˈsiːkwəl/ ("sequel"), mirroring the language's prerelease development name, "SEQUEL".
[src:materialize-db/sql] The standard is commonly denoted by the pattern: *ISO/IEC 9075-n:yyyy Part n: title*, or, as a shortcut, *ISO/IEC 9075*.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Interested parties may purchase the standards documents from ISO, IEC, or ANSI.
[src:materialize-db/sql] SQL is designed for a specific purpose: to query data contained in a relational database.
[src:materialize-db/sql] SQL is a set-based, declarative programming language, not an imperative programming language like C or BASIC.
[src:materialize-db/sql] However, extensions to Standard SQL add procedural programming language functionality, such as control-of-flow constructs.
[src:materialize-db/sql] In addition to the standard SQL/PSM extensions and proprietary SQL extensions, procedural and object-oriented programmability is available on many SQL platforms via DBMS integration with other languages.
[src:materialize-db/sql] The SQL standard defines SQL/JRT extensions (SQL Routines and Types for the Java Programming Language) to support Java code in SQL databases.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Microsoft SQL Server 2005 uses the SQLCLR (SQL Server Common Language Runtime) to host managed .NET assemblies in the database, while prior versions of SQL Server were restricted to unmanaged extended stored procedures primarily written in C.
[src:materialize-db/sql] PostgreSQL lets users write functions in a wide variety of languages—including Perl, Python, Tcl, JavaScript (PL/V8) and C.
[src:materialize-db/sql] A distinction should be made between alternatives to SQL as a language, and alternatives to the relational model itself.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Below are proposed relational alternatives to the SQL language.
[src:materialize-db/sql] See navigational database and NoSQL for alternatives to the relational model.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM from 1988 to 1994.
[src:materialize-db/sql] DRDA enables network-connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:materialize-db/sql] An interactive user or program can issue SQL statements to a local RDB and receive tables of data and status indicators in reply from remote RDBs.
[src:materialize-db/sql] SQL statements can also be compiled and stored in remote RDBs as packages and then invoked by package name.
[src:materialize-db/sql] This is important for the efficient operation of application programs that issue complex, high-frequency queries.
[src:materialize-db/sql] It is especially important when the tables to be accessed are located in remote systems.
[src:materialize-db/sql] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Distributed SQL processing ala DRDA is distinctive from contemporary distributed SQL databases.
[src:materialize-db/sql] SQL deviates in several ways from its theoretical foundation, the relational model and its tuple calculus.
[src:materialize-db/sql] In that model, a table is a set of tuples, while in SQL, tables and query results are lists of rows; the same row may occur multiple times, and the order of rows can be employed in queries (e.g., in the `LIMIT` clause).
[src:materialize-db/sql] Critics argue that SQL should be replaced with a language that returns strictly to the original foundation: for example, see *The Third Manifesto* by Hugh Darwen and C.J.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Early specifications did not support major features, such as primary keys.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Result sets could not be named, and subqueries had not been defined.
[src:materialize-db/sql] The lack of sum types has been described as a roadblock to full use of SQL's user-defined types.
[src:materialize-db/sql] JSON support, for example, needed to be added by a new standard in 2016.
[src:materialize-db/sql] The concept of Null is the subject of some debate.
[src:materialize-db/sql] The Null marker indicates the absence of a value, and is distinct from a value of 0 for an integer column or an empty string for a text column.
[src:materialize-db/sql] The concept of Nulls enforces the 3-valued-logic in SQL, which is a concrete implementation of the general 3-valued logic.
[src:materialize-db/sql] Another popular criticism is that it allows duplicate rows, making integration with languages such as Python, whose data types might make accurately representing the data difficult, in terms of parsing and by the absence of modularity.
[src:materialize-db/sql] This is usually avoided by declaring a primary key, or a unique constraint, with one or more columns that uniquely identify a row in the table.
[src:materialize-db/sql] In a sense similar to object–relational impedance mismatch, a mismatch occurs between the declarative SQL language and the procedural languages in which SQL is typically embedded.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] In computer science, **stream processing** (also known as **event stream processing**, **data stream processing**, or **distributed stream processing**) is a programming paradigm which views streams, or sequences of events in time, as the central input and output objects of computation.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Stream processing encompasses dataflow programming, reactive programming, and distributed data processing.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Stream processing systems use streaming algorithms to trace parallel processing for data streams.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] The stream processing paradigm simplifies parallel software and hardware by restricting the parallel computation that can be performed.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Given a sequence of data (a *stream*), a series of operations (*kernel functions*) is applied to each element in the stream.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Kernel functions are usually pipelined, and optimal local on-chip memory reuse is attempted, in order to minimize the loss in bandwidth, associated with external memory interaction.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] *Uniform streaming*, where one kernel function is applied to all elements in the stream, is typical.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Since the kernel and stream abstractions expose data dependencies, compiler tools can fully automate and optimize on-chip management tasks.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Stream processing hardware can use scoreboarding, for example, to initiate a direct memory access (DMA) when dependencies become known.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] The elimination of manual DMA management reduces software complexity, and an associated elimination for hardware cached I/O, reduces the data area expanse that has to be involved with service by specialized computational units such as arithmetic logic units.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] During the 1980s stream processing was explored within dataflow programming.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] An example is the language SISAL (Streams and Iteration in a Single Assignment Language).
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Stream processing is essentially a compromise, driven by a data-centric model that works very well for traditional DSP or GPU-type applications (such as image, video and digital signal processing) but less so for general purpose processing with more randomized data access (such as databases).
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] By sacrificing some flexibility in the model, the implications allow easier, faster and more efficient execution.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Depending on the context, processor design may be tuned for maximum efficiency or a trade-off for flexibility.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] For each record we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] By way of illustration, the following code fragments demonstrate detection of patterns within event streams.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] The first is an example of processing a data stream using a continuous SQL query (a query that executes forever processing arriving data based on timestamps and window duration).
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] This code fragment illustrates a JOIN of two data streams, one for stock orders, and one for the resulting stock trades.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] The query outputs a stream of all Orders matched by a Trade within one second of the Order being placed.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] The output stream is sorted by timestamp, in this case, the timestamp from the Orders stream.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Another sample code fragment detects weddings among a flow of external "events" such as church bells ringing, the appearance of a man in a tuxedo or morning suit, a woman in a flowing white gown and rice flying through the air.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] A "complex" or "composite" event is what one infers from the individual simple events: a wedding is happening.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Basic computers started from a sequential execution paradigm.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Traditional CPUs are SISD based, which means they conceptually perform only one operation at a time.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] As the computing needs of the world evolved, the amount of data to be managed increased very quickly.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] It was obvious that the sequential programming model could not cope with the increased need for processing power.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Various efforts have been spent on finding alternative ways to perform massive amounts of computations but the only solution was to exploit some level of parallel execution.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] The result of those efforts was SIMD, a programming paradigm which allowed applying one instruction to multiple instances of (different) data.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Most of the time, SIMD was being used in a SWAR environment.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] By using more complicated structures, one could also have MIMD parallelism.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Although those two paradigms were efficient, real-world implementations were plagued with limitations from memory alignment problems to synchronization issues and limited parallelism.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Only few SIMD processors survived as stand-alone components; most were embedded in standard CPUs.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Consider a simple program adding up two arrays containing 100 4-component vectors (i.e.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] This is the sequential paradigm that is most familiar.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Variations do exist (such as inner loops, structures and such), but they ultimately boil down to that construct.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] It assumes the instruction `vector_sum` works.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Although this is what happens with instruction intrinsics, much information is actually not taken into account here such as the number of vector components and their data format.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] You can see however, this method reduces the number of decoded instructions from *numElements * componentsPerElement* to *numElements*.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] The number of jump instructions is also decreased, as the loop is run fewer times.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] These gains result from the parallel execution of the four mathematical operations.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] What happened however is that the packed SIMD register holds a certain amount of data so it's not possible to get more parallelism.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] The speed up is somewhat limited by the assumption we made of performing four parallel operations (please note this is common for both AltiVec and SSE).
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] In this paradigm, the whole dataset is defined, rather than each component block being defined separately.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Describing the set of data is assumed to be in the first two rows.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] After that, the result is inferred from the sources and kernel.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] For simplicity, there's a 1:1 mapping between input and output data but this does not need to be.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Applied kernels can also be much more complex.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] An implementation of this paradigm can "unroll" a loop internally.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] This allows throughput to scale with chip complexity, easily utilizing hundreds of ALUs.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] The elimination of complex data patterns makes much of this extra power available.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] While stream processing is a branch of SIMD/MIMD processing, they must not be confused.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Although SIMD implementations can often work in a "streaming" manner, their performance is not comparable: the model envisions a very different usage pattern which allows far greater performance by itself.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] It has been noted that when applied on generic processors such as standard CPU, only a 1.5x speedup can be reached.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] By contrast, ad-hoc stream processors easily reach over 10x performance, mainly attributed to the more efficient memory access and higher levels of parallel processing.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Although there are various degrees of flexibility allowed by the model, stream processors usually impose some limitations on the kernel or stream size.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] For example, consumer hardware often lacks the ability to perform high-precision math, lacks complex indirection chains or presents lower limits on the number of instructions which can be executed.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Stanford University stream processing projects included the Stanford Real-Time Programmable Shading Project started in 1999.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] A prototype called Imagine was developed in 2002.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] A project called Merrimac ran until about 2004.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] AT&T also researched stream-enhanced processors as graphics processing units rapidly evolved in both speed and functionality.[1] Since these early days, dozens of stream processing languages have been developed, as well as specialized hardware.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] The most immediate challenge in the realm of parallel processing does not lie as much in the type of hardware architecture used, but in how easy it will be to program the system in question in a real-world environment with acceptable performance.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Machines like Imagine use a straightforward single-threaded model with automated dependencies, memory allocation and DMA scheduling.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] This in itself is a result of the research at MIT and Stanford in finding an optimal *layering of tasks* between programmer, tools and hardware.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Programmers beat tools in mapping algorithms to parallel hardware, and tools beat programmers in figuring out smartest memory allocation schemes, etc.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Of particular concern are MIMD designs such as Cell, for which the programmer needs to deal with application partitioning across multiple cores and deal with process synchronization and load balancing.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] A drawback of SIMD programming was the issue of array-of-structures (AoS) and structure-of-arrays (SoA).
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] When multiple of these structures exist in memory they are placed end to end creating an arrays in an *array of structures* (AoS) topology.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] This means that should some algorithm be applied to the location of each particle in turn it must skip over memory locations containing the other attributes.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] If these attributes are not needed this results in wasteful usage of the CPU cache.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Additionally, a SIMD instruction will typically expect the data it will operate on to be contiguous in memory, the elements may also need to be aligned.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] By moving the memory location of the data out of the structure data can be better organised for efficient access in a stream and for SIMD instructions to operate one.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] A *structure of arrays* (SoA), as shown below, can allow this.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Instead of holding the data in the structure, it holds only pointers (memory locations) for the data.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Shortcomings are that if multiple attributes to of an object are to be operated on they might now be distant in memory and so result in a cache miss.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] The aligning and any needed padding lead to increased memory usage.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Overall, memory management may be more complicated if structures are added and removed for example.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] For stream processors, the usage of structures is encouraged.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] From an application point of view, all the attributes can be defined with some flexibility.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Taking GPUs as reference, there is a set of attributes (at least 16) available.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] For each attribute, the application can state the number of components and the format of the components (but only primitive data types are supported for now).
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] The various attributes are then attached to a memory block, possibly defining a *stride* between 'consecutive' elements of the same attributes, effectively allowing interleaved data.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] When the GPU begins the stream processing, it will *gather* all the various attributes in a single set of parameters (usually this looks like a structure or a "magic global variable"), performs the operations and *scatters* the results to some memory area for later processing (or retrieving).
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] More modern stream processing frameworks provide a FIFO like interface to structure data as a literal stream.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] This abstraction provides a means to specify data dependencies implicitly while enabling the runtime/hardware to take full advantage of that knowledge for efficient computation.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] One of the simplest and most efficient stream processing modalities to date for C++, is RaftLib, which enables linking independent compute kernels together as a data flow graph using C++ stream operators.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Apart from specifying streaming applications in high-level languages, models of computation (MoCs) also have been widely used as dataflow models and process-based models.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Historically, CPUs began implementing various tiers of memory access optimizations because of the ever-increasing performance when compared to relatively slow growing external memory bandwidth.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] As this gap widened, big amounts of die area were dedicated to hiding memory latencies.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Since fetching information and opcodes to those few ALUs is expensive, very little die area is dedicated to actual mathematical machinery (as a rough estimation, consider it to be less than 10%).
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] A similar architecture exists on stream processors but thanks to the new programming model, the amount of transistors dedicated to management is actually very little.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Beginning from a whole system point of view, stream processors usually exist in a controlled environment.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] GPUs do exist on an add-in board (this seems to also apply to Imagine).
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] CPUs continue do the job of managing system resources, running applications, and such.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] The stream processor is usually equipped with a fast, efficient, proprietary memory bus (crossbar switches are now common, multi-buses have been employed in the past).
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] The exact amount of memory lanes is dependent on the market range.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] As this is written, there are still 64-bit wide interconnections around (entry-level).
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Most mid-range models use a fast 128-bit crossbar switch matrix (4 or 2 segments), while high-end models deploy huge amounts of memory (actually up to 512 MB) with a slightly slower crossbar that is 256 bits wide.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] By contrast, standard processors from Intel Pentium to some Athlon 64 have only a single 64-bit wide data bus.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Memory access patterns are much more predictable.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] While arrays do exist, their dimension is fixed at kernel invocation.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] The thing which most closely matches a multiple pointer indirection is an *indirection chain*, which is however guaranteed to finally read or write from a specific memory area (inside a stream).
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Because of the SIMD nature of the stream processor's execution units (ALUs clusters), read/write operations are expected to happen in bulk, so memories are optimized for high bandwidth rather than low latency (this is a difference from Rambus and DDR SDRAM, for example).
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] This also allows for efficient memory bus negotiations.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Most (90%) of a stream processor's work is done on-chip, requiring only 1% of the global data to be stored to memory.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] This is where knowing the kernel temporaries and dependencies pays.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Internally, a stream processor features some clever communication and management circuits but what's interesting is the *Stream Register File* (SRF).
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] This is conceptually a large cache in which stream data is stored to be transferred to external memory in bulks.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] As a cache-like software-controlled structure to the various ALUs, the SRF is shared between all the various ALU clusters.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] The key concept and innovation here done with Stanford's Imagine chip is that the compiler is able to automate and allocate memory in an optimal way, fully transparent to the programmer.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] The dependencies between kernel functions and data is known through the programming model which enables the compiler to perform flow analysis and optimally pack the SRFs.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Commonly, this cache and DMA management can take up the majority of a project's schedule, something the stream processor (or at least Imagine) totally automates.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Tests done at Stanford showed that the compiler did an as well or better job at scheduling memory than if you hand tuned the thing with much effort.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] There is proof; there can be a lot of clusters because inter-cluster communication is assumed to be rare.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Internally however, each cluster can efficiently exploit a much lower amount of ALUs because intra-cluster communication is common and thus needs to be highly efficient.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] To keep those ALUs fetched with data, each ALU is equipped with local register files (LRFs), which are basically its usable registers.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] This three-tiered data access pattern, makes it easy to keep temporary data away from slow memories, thus making the silicon implementation highly efficient and power-saving.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Although an order of magnitude speedup can be reasonably expected (even from mainstream GPUs when computing in a streaming manner), not all applications benefit from this.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Communication latencies are actually the biggest problem.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Although PCI Express improved this with full-duplex communications, getting a GPU (and possibly a generic stream processor) to work will possibly take long amounts of time.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] This means it's usually counter-productive to use them for small datasets.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Because changing the kernel is a rather expensive operation the stream architecture also incurs penalties for small streams, a behaviour referred to as the *short stream effect*.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Pipelining is a very widespread and heavily used practice on stream processors, with GPUs featuring pipelines exceeding 200 stages.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] The cost for switching settings is dependent on the setting being modified but it is now considered to always be expensive.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] To avoid those problems at various levels of the pipeline, many techniques have been deployed such as "über shaders" and "texture atlases".
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Those techniques are game-oriented because of the nature of GPUs, but the concepts are interesting for generic stream processing as well.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Most programming languages for stream processors start with Java, C or C++ and add extensions which provide specific instructions to allow application developers to tag kernels and/or streams.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] This also applies to most shading languages, which can be considered stream programming languages to a certain degree.
[src:materialize-db/stream-processing] Commercial implementations are either general purpose or tied to specific hardware by a vendor.
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] Materialize combines the accessibility of SQL databases with a streaming engine that is horizontally scalable, highly available, and strongly consistent.
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] In traditional databases, materialized views help you avoid re-running heavy queries, typically by caching queries to serve results faster.
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] But you have to make a compromise between the freshness of the results, the cost of refreshing the view, and the complexity of the SQL statements you can use.
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] In Materialize, you don’t have to make such compromises.
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] Its engine is built on Timely and Differential Dataflow — data processing frameworks backed by many years of research and optimized for this exact purpose.
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] Like most databases, you interact with Materialize using **SQL**.
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] You can build complex analytical workloads using **any type of join** (including non-windowed joins and joins on arbitrary conditions) as well as leverage new SQL patterns enabled by streaming like **Change Data Capture (CDC)**, **temporal filters**, and **subscriptions**.
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] Materialize follows the SQL standard (SQL-92) implementation and aims for compatibility with the PostgreSQL dialect.
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] It **does not** aim for compatibility with a specific version of PostgreSQL.
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] This means that Materialize might support syntax from any released PostgreSQL version, but does not provide full coverage of the PostgreSQL dialect.
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] The implementation and performance of specific features (like window functions) might also differ, because Materialize uses an entirely different database engine based on Timely and Differential Dataflow.
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] If you need specific syntax or features that are not currently supported in Materialize, please submit a feature request.
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] For more information, see Ingest Data and Integrations.
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] Every database needs a protocol to standardize communication with the outside world.
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] Materialize uses the PostgreSQL wire protocol, which allows it to integrate out-of-the-box with many SQL clients and other tools in the data ecosystem that support PostgreSQL — like dbt.
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] Don’t see the a tool that you’d like to use with Materialize listed under Tools and integrations?
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] Let us know by submitting a feature request!
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] By default, Materialize provides the highest level of transaction isolation: **strict serializability**.
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] This means that it presents as if it were a single process, despite spanning a large number of threads, processes, and machines.
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] Strict serializability avoids common pitfalls like eventual consistency and dual writes, which affect the correctness of your results.
[src:materialize-db/what-is-materialize] You can adjust the transaction isolation level depending on your consistency and performance requirements.
